For us this speech, apart from the great attractions of the clear and graceful narrative, and the harmonious beauty of the well-rounded language, which makes it a masterpiece of the medium (mediocre) dicendi yenit-3¹¹⁵, offers the special interest that from it better than from any other relic of antiquity, we can discover the regular arrangement of a speech belonging to the deliberative class. The third section of the argument may at the same time be regarded as a model of the demonstrativum yenus causarum, a kind of oratory which is employed hardly anywhere besides in the time of the Roman republic, except in the

laudationes funebres ¹¹⁶.
